            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ivan Miller is a man who knows the secrets of the city, not its scandals, but its pulse. Born and raised in a fading Ohio steel town, his upbringing was defined by the scent of rust and the anxiety of his factory-worker father\u2019s precarious employment. He saw firsthand how quickly a life built on industry could crumble. He finished high school in 1992 with no desire for college, only a powerful urge for stability and a place that was building up, not tearing down. With two hundred dollars and a cousin\u2019s address, he took a bus to San Francisco.\n\nHis early years in the city were a blur of construction gigs and manual labor jobs. He learned wiring, plumbing, and the satisfaction of a hard day's work. His big break came in his late twenties when he landed a position with the San Francisco Public Utilities Commission. It was a union job with benefits and a pension\u2014the kind of security his father had only dreamed of.\n\nA key turning point came after his divorce. The marriage had buckled under the weight of long hours and Ivan\u2019s reserved nature. Newly single in his late 30s and seeking solitude, he took an unusual internal transfer: on-site caretaker for a small, unassuming water pumping station nestled in the Outer Sunset. This explains his 0.0-mile commute; he lives in a small, city-owned apartment attached to the facility he maintains.\n\nNow at 50, Ivan\u2019s life is governed by the hum of machinery. His routine is a quiet loop of system checks, maintenance, and monitoring the flow of water to thousands of homes. He is a ghost in the neighborhood\u2014a familiar but unknown face to the dog walkers and families who pass the brick building he calls home. His primary social connection is his grown daughter, an architect in Portland, with whom he has weekly video calls. He sees the changing tides of San Francisco\u2014the tech booms, the housing crises\u2014as distant weather patterns. His concern is the pressure in the pipes, the literal lifeblood of the city. His dream is a simple one: retire in a decade to a small plot of land near the Russian River, where the only flow he\u2019ll have to worry about is the current."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the finality of the Greyhound bus pulling away from the depot in 1992. Through the grimy window, he watched the last Ohio smokestack shrink against a grey sky until it was just a pinprick, then gone. It wasn\u2019t triumph he felt, but a deep, gut-level release, like a breath held for eighteen years. In that moment, he wasn't just leaving home; he was shedding a future of rust and worry. That quiet resolve to never go back solidified into the foundation of the man he would become.\n\n2.\nIn his late twenties, Ivan stood in his cramped Mission apartment holding the official offer letter from the SFPUC. The paper felt heavy, substantial. He saw his father\u2019s face in his mind\u2014the permanent crease of anxiety between his brows, the hands stained with grease and failure. A wave of profound, unfamiliar security washed over him. This piece of paper wasn't just a job; it was a pension, benefits, an anchor. It was the promise he\u2019d made to his younger self, fulfilled. It was the end of a long escape.\n\n3.\nHis first night living at the pumping station was the quietest of his life. The divorce was final, the small apartment sterile and empty. But through the wall came a low, constant hum\u2014the sound of the pumps moving water across the city. It wasn't lonely; it was a rhythmic, mechanical heartbeat. That steady thrum filled the silence left by his marriage, offering a companionship that asked for nothing but maintenance. He realized then that he preferred the reliable pulse of machinery to the unpredictable cadence of a human heart.\n\n4.\nDuring a fierce winter storm around 2015, an alarm jolted him awake at 3 a.m. A pressure drop. In the rain-lashed dark, he worked for an hour, tracing the fault to a secondary valve. As he manually restored the flow, he felt the immense, invisible weight of the sleeping neighborhoods around him. He wasn't just a caretaker; he was a gatekeeper, the unseen man ensuring the city\u2019s lifeblood didn\u2019t stop. The feeling was a quiet, immense pride that warmed him better than any coffee could.\n\n5.\nOn a recent video call, his daughter, the architect, showed him blueprints for a building in Portland. She asked a technical question about the station's seismic reinforcements. He explained the redundant systems, the fail-safes. He saw a flicker of deep, professional respect in her eyes. In that moment, his world of pipes and gauges connected to her world of design and glass. His hidden, blue-collar work was seen and understood by the person who mattered most. It was, he thought, the purest form of love he knew."
        },
